'''Johnny Robinson''' (1947–1963) was a young [[African Americans|African-American]] man who, at age 16, was shot and killed by a police officer in the unrest following the [[16th Street Baptist Church bombing|16th Street Church Bombing]] in [[Birmingham, Alabama]]. Robinson and several others were allegedly throwing rocks at a car draped with a [[Flags of the Confederate States of America|Confederate flag]]. A Birmingham police officer, Jack Parker, who was riding in the back seat of a police car, shot and killed Robinson. Parker was never indicted for the killing and claimed that he had only fired a warning shot, and that a stray pellet must have killed Robinson.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Eskew|first1=Glenn T|title=But for Birmingham: The Local and National Movements in the Civil Rights Struggle|date=1997|publisher=the University of North carolina Press|pages=320–321|accessdate=27 March 2017}}</ref>
==Background and early years== Johnny Robinson was born in 1947 and had a difficult upbringing in Birmingham, as the city had seen 50 racially driven bombings from 1945 to 1963. He was the oldest of three children and attended the [[Alberta Shields School]]. A few years prior to his death, Robinson's father was murdered by a neighbor, leaving his mother alone to raise her children in a city fraught with racial violence.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.biography.com/people/johnny-robinson-21443815|title=Johnny Robinson|website=Biography|language=en-us|access-date=2018-09-16}}</ref> Robinson had juvenile record. At 13 years old he was arrested on suspicion of [[burglary]] and [[grand larceny]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=129856740|title=Johnny's Death: The Untold Tragedy In Birmingham|work=NPR.org|access-date=2018-09-16|language=en}}</ref>
==Events== {{see also|16th Street Baptist Church bombing}} Early on Sunday morning, September 15, 1963, a [[Ku Klux Klan]] member placed a bomb with a timing device under the side steps of the [[16th Street Baptist Church]], which had served as the headquarters for the [[Children's Crusade (1963)|Birmingham Children's Crusade]] during April and early May.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.biography.com/news/black-history-birmingham-childrens-crusade-1963-video|title=The Birmingham Children's Crusade of 1963|work=Biography.com|access-date=2017-04-18|language=en-us}}</ref> Two hundred worshipers were expected in the church that day and after the bomb detonated in the late morning, three 14-year-old girls and an 11-year-old girl were found killed, with twenty-two wounded. The incident prompted civil unrest that was further provoked by the shooting deaths of two young black men that day: 16-year-old Johnny Robinson, and 13-year-old Virgil Ware.
Ware had been riding on the handlebars of his brother's bicycle when he was shot twice with a revolver by Larry Joe Sims, a white 16-year-old who supported the segregationist movement. Earlier that day, Sims had joined a fellow teenager, Michael Lee Farley, at the headquarters for the [[National States' Rights Party]] and set out to cruise the neighborhood together.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=u9p6CwAAQBAJ&pg=PA50&lpg=PA50&dq=National+States'+Rights+Party+sims&source=bl&ots=ZQT28h5KbS&sig=H9qZfs7yf3E2VT0qBjLFjT5ohqM&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjf4Jyy2fTTAhVP3GMKHe6uDEMQ6AEIMjAB#v=onepage&q=National%20States'%20Rights%20Party%20sims&f=false|title=Unsolved Civil Rights Murder Cases, 1934–1970|last=Newton|first=Michael|date=2016-01-08|publisher=McFarland|year=|isbn=9781476623627|location=|pages=50|language=en}}</ref> Sims was later charged with [[Murder|first-degree murder]] but was convicted of [[Manslaughter (United States law)|second-degree manslaughter]], while Farley pled guilty to second-degree manslaughter. Both teens were sentenced to seven months in jail, which was changed to two years probation.<ref name=":0" />{{relevance inline|date=September 2017}}
Robinson was about to join his sister for [[Sunday dinner]], but had accompanied his friends to a gas station that was not far from the 16th Street Baptist Church. Several [[Caucasian race|Caucasian]] men drove by, yelling racial slurs, waving Confederate flags, and throwing bottles. Robinson and his friends allegedly retaliated by throwing rocks at the cars. A police car then arrived on the scene; a police officer named Jack Parker was in the back seat, pointing a shotgun out the window.<ref>{{cite web|title=Johnny's Death: The Untold Tragedy In Birmingham|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=129856740|website=NPR.org|accessdate=27 February 2017|language=en}}</ref> Parker later gave two differing accounts of the event, as he both claimed to have fired a [[warning shot]] and that the gun went off accidentally.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=http://www.biography.com/people/johnny-robinson-21443815|title=Johnny Robinson|website=Biography.com|language=en-us|access-date=2017-04-18}}</ref> Witnesses claimed to have heard two shots.{{citation needed|date=September 2017}}
Parker was white, as were all Birmingham Police officers at that time.<ref>"New Bomb Blast Hits Birmingham". The Miami News. 1963-09-25.</ref> He had joined the police force in 1951 and was 48 years old when he shot Robinson. At the time he was also the head of a [[Fraternal Order of Police]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Dividing Lines: Municipal Politics and the Struggle for Civil Rights in Montgomery, Birmingham, and Selma|last=Thronton|first=J|publisher=University of Alabama Press, 2002|year=|isbn=081731170X|location=|pages=346}}</ref>
==Aftermath==
After a week of funerals related to the bombing, co-founder of the [[Alabama Christian Movement for Human Rights]] Nelson Smith remarked that their people would be hard to restrain when they were still under active threat of bombings.<ref name="mills">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XC7DlNowvSkC&pg=PA346|title=Dividing Lines: Municipal Politics and the Struggle for Civil Rights in Montgomery, Birmingham, and Selma|last=Thornton|first=J. Mills|publisher=University of Alabama Press|year=2002|isbn=9780817311704|location=Tuscaloosa|pages=346–47}}</ref>{{Not in source given|date=May 2017}}
Two grand juries refused to indict Parker, claiming that there were no reliable witness accounts. Not long after the shooting, he signed a newspaper advertisement advocating against integrating the police department of Birmingham. He resigned 10&nbsp;years after the shooting.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Student Voice. 1960-1965|date=1990|page=212|edition=Clayborne Carson|accessdate=27 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.justice.gov/crt/case-document/officer-jack-parker-deceased-birmingham-police-dept-birmingham-alabama-subject|title=Johnnie Robinson - Notice to Close File {{!}} CRT {{!}} Department of Justice|website=www.justice.gov|language=en|access-date=2017-02-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Timothy Hughes newspaper|url=http://www.rarenewspapers.com/view/604242|website=Rare and Early News|accessdate=13 February 2017}}</ref>
